FGETWS(3)                                                                       Linux Programmer's Manual                                                                       FGETWS(3)

NNAAMMEE
       fgetws - read a wide-character string from a FILE stream

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<wwcchhaarr..hh>>

       wwcchhaarr__tt **ffggeettwwss((wwcchhaarr__tt **_w_s,, iinntt _n,, FFIILLEE **_s_t_r_e_a_m));;

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       The ffggeettwwss() function is the wide-character equivalent of the ffggeettss(3) function.  It reads a string of at most _n_-_1 wide characters into the wide-character array pointed to by _w_s,
       and adds a terminating null wide character (L'\0').  It stops reading wide characters after it has encountered and stored a newline wide character.  It also  stops  when  end  of
       stream is reached.

       The programmer must ensure that there is room for at least _n wide characters at _w_s.

       For a nonlocking counterpart, see uunnlloocckkeedd__ssttddiioo(3).

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
       The ffggeettwwss() function, if successful, returns _w_s.  If end of stream was already reached or if an error occurred, it returns NULL.

AATTTTRRIIBBUUTTEESS
       For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see aattttrriibbuutteess(7).

       ┌──────────┬───────────────┬─────────┐
       │IInntteerrffaaccee │ AAttttrriibbuuttee     │ VVaalluuee   │
       ├──────────┼───────────────┼─────────┤
       │ffggeettwwss()  │ Thread safety │ MT-Safe │
       └──────────┴───────────────┴─────────┘
CCOONNFFOORRMMIINNGG TTOO
       POSIX.1-2001, POSIX.1-2008, C99.

NNOOTTEESS
       The behavior of ffggeettwwss() depends on the LLCC__CCTTYYPPEE category of the current locale.

       In the absence of additional information passed to the ffooppeenn(3) call, it is reasonable to expect that ffggeettwwss() will actually read a multibyte string from the stream and then con‐
       vert it to a wide-character string.

       This function is unreliable, because it does not permit to deal properly with null wide characters that may be present in the input.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       ffggeettwwcc(3), uunnlloocckkeedd__ssttddiioo(3)

CCOOLLOOPPHHOONN
